    favquote:
      "A disgraced journalist and a brilliant but troubled hacker investigate the decades-old disappearance of a wealthy industrialist's niece.",
    description:
      "The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo is the first installment of Stieg Larsson's Millennium Trilogy, a landmark work of Scandinavian crime fiction that combines intricate mystery plotting with deep social commentary and unforgettable character creation. The novel introduces two protagonists whose unlikely partnership drives the narrative: Mikael Blomkvist, a respected financial journalist who has just lost a libel suit against a corrupt industrialist, leaving his reputation and his magazine, Millennium, in jeopardy; and Lisbeth Salander, a brilliant but deeply troubled young hacker whose photographic memory, computer skills, and history of institutional abuse have made her an outsider to mainstream society. The novel's structure reflects Larsson's background as a journalist and political activist, weaving together corporate corruption, investigative journalism, and the ongoing crisis of violence against women in Sweden. The plot is set in motion when Henrik Vanger, the aging patriarch of a powerful industrial family, hires Blomkvist to investigate the disappearance of his niece Harriet, who vanished from the family's private island forty years earlier. As Blomkvist delves into the Vanger family's dark history, he uncovers evidence of serial murder, Nazi sympathies, and generations of cruelty, while Lisbeth, initially hired to investigate Blomkvist himself, becomes an essential partner in the investigation. Larsson's depiction of Lisbeth Salander is one of modern fiction's most memorable character creations—a woman whose piercings, tattoos, and apparent social dysfunction mask a fierce intelligence, a rigid moral code, and a capacity for violence born from years of abuse at the hands of the state's guardians. The novel's Swedish title, Män som hatar kvinnor (Men Who Hate Women), more accurately reflects its central concern with misogyny and violence against women, themes that Larsson had spent his career exposing as a journalist. The investigation gradually reveals a series of murders connected to biblical passages and misogynistic ideology, while Lisbeth's own story—including her rape by her legal guardian and her brutal revenge—forms a parallel narrative about the failure of Swedish institutions to protect vulnerable women. Larsson died of a heart attack in 2004, shortly after delivering the manuscripts for the first three novels, and never saw their publication or the international phenomenon they became. The Millennium Trilogy has sold over 80 million copies worldwide, making Larsson one of the best-selling authors of the 21st century and sparking a wave of interest in Scandinavian crime fiction. The novel's success can be attributed to its combination of classic mystery structure with contemporary social concerns, its morally complex protagonists, and its unflinching examination of dark subjects often treated with evasion. The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo has been adapted into Swedish and American films, further cementing Lisbeth Salander's status as a cultural icon, and its influence can be seen in the many strong female characters and socially conscious crime narratives that followed in its wake.",
