    binding: ["Paperback", "Hardcover", "Audiobook", "E-book"],
    favquote:
      "A young man sells his soul for eternal youth, while his portrait ages and bears the marks of his moral decay.",
    description:
      "The Picture of Dorian Gray is Oscar Wilde's only novel, a masterpiece of Gothic fiction that scandalized Victorian society with its frank exploration of hedonism, aestheticism, and the dark consequences of a life lived without moral restraint. The novel tells the story of Dorian Gray, a beautiful young man whose portrait, painted by his friend Basil Hallward, captures his physical perfection. Under the influence of Lord Henry Wotton, a cynical aristocrat who preaches a philosophy of pleasure-seeking and self-indulgence, Dorian makes a fateful wish: that the portrait would age and bear the marks of his sins while he remains forever young and beautiful. As Dorian pursues a life of increasingly debauched pleasure, he discovers that his wish has been granted—the portrait grows increasingly hideous, reflecting the corruption of his soul, while his own face remains untouched by time or consequence. The novel traces Dorian's descent from naive youth to calculating monster, as his actions lead to the suicide of his first love, the actress Sibyl Vane, and eventually to the murder of Basil, the one man who loved him for his true self. Wilde uses the portrait as a powerful symbol of the divided self, the hidden conscience that records what society refuses to see, and the inevitable cost of denying moral reality. The novel is also a vehicle for Wilde's wit and aesthetic philosophy, with Lord Henry serving as a mouthpiece for the provocative ideas that made Wilde both famous and infamous: that art has no moral purpose, that beauty is the only value worth pursuing, and that self-realization justifies any action. Yet the novel itself becomes a cautionary tale that undermines Lord Henry's philosophy, showing that the pursuit of pleasure without responsibility leads not to freedom but to enslavement, not to fulfillment but to emptiness. The Picture of Dorian Gray was first published in 1890 in Lippincott's Monthly Magazine, where it was condemned as immoral by critics who objected to its homoerotic undertones and its frank treatment of decadence. Wilde revised and expanded the novel for book publication in 1891, adding chapters that made the moral consequences more explicit and including a preface that has become one of his most famous writings, in which he argues that 'There is no such thing as a moral or an immoral book. Books are well written, or badly written. That is all.' Despite—or perhaps because of—its notoriety, the novel was used as evidence against Wilde during his trial for gross indecency, leading to his imprisonment and ruin. The Picture of Dorian Gray has since been recognized as a classic of Gothic literature and a key text of the Aesthetic movement, its influence extending through the decadent literature of the 1890s to the modern horror tradition and beyond. The novel's exploration of the relationship between art and morality, its critique of Victorian hypocrisy, and its portrait of a soul corrupted by its own desires continue to resonate with readers who recognize in Dorian Gray's tragedy the universal human struggle between the face we present to the world and the self we hide from it. The novel's famous conclusion—Dorian's attempt to destroy the portrait, which instead destroys him, leaving the painting restored to its original beauty and his body aged and hideous—offers a powerful meditation on the impossibility of escaping the consequences of one's choices, however artfully one may hide them.",
