      "The Fault in Our Stars is a landmark work of young adult literature that transcended its genre to become one of the most beloved and widely read novels of the 21st century, a story about love, mortality, and the search for meaning that has touched millions of readers around the world. John Green's sixth novel, published in 2012, tells the story of Hazel Grace Lancaster, a sixteen-year-old who has been living with terminal thyroid cancer since she was thirteen, her lungs so compromised that she carries an oxygen tank everywhere she goes. Hazel's life is defined by her illness, by the watching of reality television, by her obsession with a novel called An Imperial Affliction, and by her mother's insistence that she attend a cancer support group where she might make friends. It is at this support group that Hazel meets Augustus Waters, a seventeen-year-old former basketball player who lost his leg to osteosarcoma but is now in remission, a young man whose charm, intelligence, and insistence on living fully challenge everything Hazel believes about what her life can be. The novel's title comes from a line in Shakespeare's Julius Caesar—'The fault, dear Brutus, is not in our stars, but in ourselves'—and Green's novel is fundamentally about the question of whether our lives are determined by forces beyond our control or whether we have the power to choose how we live, even when our choices are radically constrained. Hazel and Augustus's love story is complicated by Hazel's terminal diagnosis, by her refusal to become a 'grenade' who will hurt those who love her when she dies, by their shared obsession with the elusive author of Hazel's favorite book, and by the discovery that Augustus's cancer has returned, that his remission was not permanent, and that he will die before her. The novel is notable for its intellectual ambition, incorporating discussions of literature, philosophy, and theology into the fabric of the love story, treating its teenage protagonists with the seriousness and complexity usually reserved for adult characters. Hazel's voice is sharp, funny, and deeply self-aware, her narration refusing the sentimentality that often characterizes stories about young people with cancer. Augustus's character—his obsession with heroism, his fear of oblivion, his desire to leave a mark on the world—provides a counterpoint to Hazel's quiet acceptance of her own insignificance. Their trip to Amsterdam to find Peter Van Houten, the reclusive author of An Imperial Affliction, becomes a journey of disillusionment when they discover that Van Houten is not the wise mentor they imagined but a bitter alcoholic who cannot give them the answers they seek. The novel's treatment of illness is notable for its honesty: the physical realities of cancer, the indignities of treatment, the way illness shapes every aspect of life without becoming the only thing that matters. Green, who worked as a chaplain in a children's hospital before becoming a writer, brings an authenticity to the medical aspects of the story that grounds its more philosophical elements in the concrete reality of illness. The Fault in Our Stars was a massive commercial success, spending over a year on the New York Times bestseller list, selling millions of copies worldwide, and being adapted into a critically acclaimed film that became one of the highest-grossing romantic dramas of all time. The novel's success made John Green one of the most famous authors of his generation and established a new model for young adult literature that combined intellectual ambition with emotional intensity. The novel's exploration of what it means to live well in the face of death, the value of love even when it is cut short, and the possibility of meaning in a universe that offers no guarantees has resonated with readers far beyond its target audience. The novel's most famous passage—'I fell in love the way you fall asleep: slowly, and then all at once'—has become one of the most quoted lines in contemporary literature, a testament to Green's ability to capture the experience of love in language that feels both universal and intimately personal. The Fault in Our Stars remains a defining work of 21st-century young adult literature, a novel that proved that stories about young people could address the deepest questions of human existence without sacrificing emotional honesty or literary ambition.",
