    description:
      "The Secret History is one of the most influential and beloved novels of the 1990s, a debut work of extraordinary sophistication that established Donna Tartt as a major literary voice and created a template for the campus novel that has been imitated but never equaled. Published in 1992 to extraordinary critical acclaim, The Secret History tells the story of Richard Papen, a young man from a working-class California background who transfers to Hampden College, a small, elite liberal arts institution in Vermont, hoping to escape his past and remake himself among the privileged children of the East Coast establishment. Richard's ambition is to join the small, exclusive classics program taught by the charismatic Julian Morrow, a man whose eccentric brilliance has attracted a select group of students who study ancient Greek in an atmosphere of intellectual intensity and cultivated isolation. The group—Henry Winter, the intellectual leader whose brilliance masks a dangerous instability; the twins Charles and Camilla Macaulay, whose relationship blurs the boundaries between sibling love and something more; Francis Abernathy, the wealthy, closeted aesthete; and Bunny Corcoran, the group's least intelligent and most conventional member—represents everything Richard believes he wants: sophistication, intellect, belonging. The novel's structure is one of its most distinctive features: the murder that drives the plot is revealed in the first sentence—'The snow in the mountains was melting and Bunny had been dead for several weeks before we came to understand the gravity of our situation'—and the novel then proceeds to explain how a group of classics students came to kill one of their own. This inversion of the traditional mystery structure allows Tartt to focus not on who committed the murder or why, but on the psychological consequences of the act, the way that killing transforms the group, the paranoia and guilt that consume them, and the question of whether it is possible to return to ordinary life after crossing the line into violence. The novel is deeply engaged with the traditions of Greek tragedy that its characters study, and its structure echoes the form of classical drama, with the murder functioning as the act of hubris that leads inevitably to the tragedy's conclusion. The Secret History is also a meditation on the nature of beauty and its relationship to morality, on the dangers of intellectual elitism, and on the ways that the pursuit of aesthetic perfection can lead to ethical blindness. The group's obsession with the ancient world, their desire to live a life of beauty and intensity beyond the reach of ordinary morality, leads them to commit an act that destroys them not because they are caught—though they are—but because the act itself changes them in ways they cannot undo. Tartt's prose is extraordinary, combining the narrative drive of a thriller with the psychological depth of literary fiction, and her depiction of the closed world of the classics program, with its reading of ancient Greek in Latin, its study of ritual and ecstasy, its isolation from the larger campus, is so fully realized that the novel has been described as creating a world readers can inhabit. The Secret History was a massive commercial and critical success, spending thirteen weeks on the New York Times bestseller list and establishing Tartt as a major literary voice. Its influence can be seen in the countless novels that followed in its wake, from the campus thrillers of the 1990s to the current boom in dark academia fiction. The novel's exploration of the relationship between intellectual ambition and moral corruption, its depiction of the seductive dangers of elitism, and its unforgettable characters have made it a touchstone for readers who return to it again and again, finding new depths in its pages with each reading. The Secret History remains essential reading for anyone interested in the possibilities of literary fiction, a novel that demonstrates how the conventions of genre can be used to explore the deepest questions of human existence, and a work that, more than thirty years after its publication, continues to find new readers who are drawn into its world and never quite escape its spell.",
