    description:
      "Circe is a masterwork of mythological fiction that reimagines one of the most fascinating figures in Greek mythology, giving voice to a character who has been, for thousands of years, a footnote in the stories of more famous men. Madeline Miller's second novel, published in 2018, tells the story of Circe, the daughter of the sun god Helios and the nymph Perse, who is born into a world of divine power and cruelty and who must forge her own path outside the structures that were meant to contain her. The novel follows Circe from her birth in the halls of her father's palace, where she is considered an embarrassment by her divine relatives—too mortal, too weak, too strange—through her exile to the island of Aiaia, where she discovers and hones her powers of witchcraft, through her encounters with the figures of Greek mythology: Hermes, who becomes a lover and betrayer; Daedalus, who finds refuge on her island after his fall; Medea, whose story parallels her own; and, most famously, Odysseus, whose year-long stay on her island becomes the centerpiece of her story but not its conclusion. Miller's novel is notable for its deep engagement with the source material, drawing on the Odyssey, the Homeric Hymns, and the traditions of Greek mythology while transforming them into a narrative that speaks to contemporary concerns. Circe's story is one of self-creation, of a woman who refuses the roles that the divine order has assigned to her and who becomes, through her own efforts, a figure of power and independence. Miller's prose is extraordinary, combining the clarity of contemporary fiction with the formal beauty appropriate to her subject, and her depiction of the natural world—the herbs and flowers that Circe uses in her witchcraft, the island that becomes her home, the sea that connects her to the world she has left behind—is vivid and immersive. The novel is also a meditation on the nature of power: the power of the gods, which is arbitrary and cruel; the power of mortals, which is brief but can be heroic; and the power of witchcraft, which is learned, earned, and wielded by those who have been excluded from other forms of authority. Circe's transformation from a figure of fear—the witch who turns men into pigs—into a figure of sympathy and admiration is one of the novel's great achievements, and Miller's treatment of her relationship with Telemachus, Odysseus's son, who comes to her island after his father's death, offers a conclusion that is both unexpected and deeply satisfying. Circe was a critical and commercial sensation upon publication, winning the Goodreads Choice Award for Fantasy, spending more than a year on the New York Times bestseller list, and being translated into more than twenty languages. Its success marked a moment in the resurgence of interest in classical mythology, part of a wave of works that reimagined ancient stories from the perspectives of women, outsiders, and those who had been silenced in the original tellings. Miller's novel stands out even in this crowded field for the depth of its characterization, the beauty of its prose, and the sophistication of its engagement with its source material. Circe is also notable for its treatment of immortality, which is usually portrayed in mythology as a gift but which Miller shows as a burden, a state of being that distances the gods from the human experiences that give life meaning. Circe's choice, at the novel's end, to become mortal, to give up her divinity for a life of limited time, is a choice for love, for human connection, and for the possibility of a life fully lived. Circe has become one of the most beloved novels of the 21st century, a work that has introduced millions of readers to Greek mythology while transforming their understanding of it. It is a novel about power and powerlessness, about the capacity to change and the courage to choose one's own path, and about the stories that survive across millennia and the ways they can be retold to reflect new understandings of the world. Madeline Miller's masterpiece is essential reading for anyone interested in the vitality of classical tradition, the possibilities of historical fiction, and the power of storytelling to reclaim voices that have been silenced for thousands of years.",
